    "body": "### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.\n\nWe currently use a lengthy utility function `__Pyx_Raise()` for raising exceptions, mostly copied from CPython, which handles all cases at runtime. But most exception raising cases are trivial and would need much less code and much less complexity, and could even run faster if there weren't so many branches.\n\n### Describe the solution you'd like.\n\nThe function should be split up into separate use cases:\n- `raise type` if we know that a builtin exception type is being raised\n- `raise instance` if we know that the code constructs an instance of a builtin exception type and then raises that\n- `raise object` if we don't know what is being raised\n\nThe utility code sections that set the exception's cause and traceback merit their own two separate functions that should be used and called only if the user code actually provides an explicit cause or traceback. In many cases, the provided cause will be a literal `None` (`raise … from None`), which is really just `PyException_SetCause(exc, NULL)` and doesn't require any additional utility code.\n\nThe fact that we allow `raise type, value, traceback` is really a relict from Python 2.x times and might continue to use a unified utility function that calls the others appropriately.\n\nWe should also switch to Vectorcall (if available, specifically in the Limited API) for instantiating the exception.\n\n### Describe alternatives you've considered.\n\n_No response_\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
